(172, 1, '2013-07-14 22:44:38', '2013-07-15 05:44:38', '<h2>1. Faithful in Reading</h2>\r\nIf you don’t read the bible, you won’t know the difference between a person’s opinion and biblical scriptures. You have to base your faith on the word of God. My opinion is no better than your opinion. My theory is no better than your theory. Focus on what the word of God says. When you read the Bible that is when the Lord is talking to you. I encourage new converts to read the New Testament several times before they go to the Old Testament. All the mysteries are hid in the Old Testament, and revealed in the New Testament.\r\n\r\nYou have to set aside time to read the Word of God. It may be hard for you to read, but as you read more, you’ll begin to have an appetite for the Word of God. When you first begin reading, don’t try to interpret it, just read it, and get acquainted with the scriptures. It’s the minister’s responsibility to give you the interpretation. In Ephesians 4, it says, The Lord ascended on high, and gave gifts unto men. Some apostles, prophets, evangelists, pastors and teachers. For what? “For the perfecting of the saints, for the work of the ministry and for the edifying of the Body of Christ. That you henceforth be no more children.” In Nehemiah 8:8, the minister read the scriptures to them and gave them the understanding of it.\r\n<h2>2. Faithful in Attending Church</h2>\r\nThe Lord should become a priority in our lives. Apostle Paul in Hebrews 10 tells us not to forsake the assembling of ourselves. It’s easy to find excuses to why we need to put other things first in our lives. I used to be an avid football player and fan, but after I got saved that didn’t mean anything to me. It’s like boys playing with a ball to me. It is important to be in church service. People come to this church because we teach the Word of God. There’s more to this than just shouting and singing. I believe it was James that put it this way, faith without works is dead.\r\n\r\nBeing faithful in attending church is not only to support the church, but it’s also for your soul. Your soul needs to be feed. We attend church three days a week; that’s not much eating. The more you stay away from church, the more carnal you become, and other things begin coming into your life that can hinder your walk with the Lord. The scriptures tell us to assemble together. It tells us we cannot be spiritual by staying home. Hebrews 10:25 says, Not forsaking the assembling of ourselves together, as the manner of some is; but exhorting one another: so much the more, as ye see the day approaching. You can’t be saved by yourself. You must get close to God and His people.\r\n<h2>3. Faithful in Worship</h2>\r\nWe must be faithful in our worship. When we come, we must participate, sing and be a part. Ephesians 5:19-20 says, Speaking to yourselves in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, singing and making melody in your heart to the Lord. Giving thanks always for all things unto God the Father in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ. Colossians 3:16 says, Let the word of Christ dwell in you richly in all wisdom; teaching and admonishing one another in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, singing with grace in your hearts to the Lord. That has to do with us worshipping when we come together.\r\n\r\nWhen Paul started the Corinthian church, he said, I fed you with milk and not with meat for you were not able to bear it. There’s milk of the Word, but if you keep using milk all the time, you will be unskilled in the word of God. Meat is the deeper things of God. Meat belongs to those who are of full age. I wouldn’t start off a new church with Revelations 13. They don’t know what the dragon or the beast is. It’s just like when you go to school; you start with the fundamentals, and then graduate into deeper things. You have to build people up to that. We must be faithful in our worship.\r\n<h2>4. Faithful in Testifying</h2>\r\nAnyone who has been converted and received the baptism of the Holy Ghost with the evidence of speaking in other tongues has a testimony of how God saved and dealt with them. We need your testimony. We need your encouragement. When you testify you’re growing and developing.\r\n\r\nHere we all have a testimony of Jesus, and what he has done for us. Every so often we all should give our full testimony – tell about the goodness of God and what He has done in our lives. Being thankful unto the Lord and testifying is important. When we testify, we edify one another. There are people that have been at the church for 30 years, and I’ve heard them testify many times. Just about every time they testify I learn something new about their testimony. I need your testimony. Your testimony encourages me in whatever I go through. All of us are going to go through trials, which is why we need to assemble ourselves together.\r\n<h2>5. Faithful in Prayer</h2>\r\nYou have to be faithful in prayer. I don’t mean going down the street praying with your eyes closed. “In 1 Thessalonians 5:17, it says, pray without ceasing. In everything give thanks: for this is the will of God in Christ Jesus concerning you. He means don’t stop praying.\r\n\r\nSometimes we’ll pray for people that are sick. It may look like the Lord is not doing anything and we’ll say, “Why pray anymore?” But we should always pray like David did when Bathsheba delivered a sick child who was close to death. David prayed and prayed in the house of God, and he mourned. Finally the child died. His servant said, “We shouldn’t tell him he’s dead because if he’s this bad what would he do if we tell him the child had passed?” Then, David asked if the child was dead, and they said, “yes.” David got up, washed his face, changed his clothes, and went into the house of God to worship. He said, “The child’s dead now, there’s no use praying. I can do no more.” But, he prayed right up to that point. It was the Lord’s will that the child didn’t live. In Luke 18:1: And he spake a parable unto them to this end, that men ought always to pray, and not to faint. What does faint mean? It means give up.\r\nWe’ve prayed for a lot of people, some of them were healed, and some were not. We should always pray because we don’t know who the Lord is going to touch. James 5:16 says, the effectual fervent prayer of the righteous man availeth much. He wasn’t talking about you praying for someone else. He was talking about your condition. We have to always pray. We pray at the beginning of our service; when we are building a church building, and at conventions we always pray for the Lord to help us make the right decisions and guide us in building.\r\n<h2>6. Faithful in Working in the Church</h2>\r\nWhen I was a young man in the church, I loved helping the people on the clean up team. I enjoyed being on the dishwashing team every Sunday when 200 or 300 people ate dinner. Did you know there’s a joy getting to know your brother and sister a lot better by being on a team? It’s great fellowship. There’s something about working in the church that helps you grow, and have responsibility.\r\n\r\nYou ask some people, do you work on a church team and they’ll respond, “Give me something to do.” No, you have to have a burden to say, “I want to do...” and I’m going to do....” My Mother use to tell me, "Y’all are lazy." I would say, "Give me a job and I’ll work. She would say, “If you were industrious, you’d find a job.” That’s the way it was back there. Working makes you a part of the church. Someone has to clean the church. It takes someone to coordinate all of this. Be faithful in working in the church.\r\n<h2>7. Faithful in Your Offering</h2>\r\nChurches don’t run off of air. Bills have to be paid. There are people in our churches who really believe in this. Sometimes I go to an elderly saint on a fixed income and say, “I bet you’re giving a little too much in the offering.” They’ll get upset because they want to give, but they also know as long as they’re faithful in church they’ll be taken care of.\r\n\r\nOnce you get the word of God to people, you don’t have to worry about giving. I never had to beg people for money. We\'ve got huge facilities worth millions of dollars on the West Coast. I’ve never sold candy, never went on the streets knocking on doors or barber shops to raise money; never did that. Not one time. If we need equipment that cost $50,000 we don’t take up a lot of time. I tell the people what we need, and just like that it’s there.\r\n\r\nI give a financial report every year. The members know what happens with the church funds? At one meeting only 18 people showed up. I said, "What’s wrong with you all? Don’t you want to know what’s going on with your money?” They said, "We see what’s going on with it." Each year since 1977, we have an outside auditor/certified public accountant, audit our books, and give us a report. He tells us if we have any weaknesses in our system. You have to be financially responsible too. You never hear of Brother Hawkins going on a junket to Israel to see where Jesus laid. Or going to go to Jordan to get two gallons of water and pour it in little bottles and tell you it’s for healing. People use all those gimmicks just to raise money. If you’re doing things right, God will supply your needs. I’ve never had to use tricks. I’ve seen people put $50 lines and $5 lines -- that’s embarrassing. What if you’re not able to give? Some faithful people in the church may fall into bad times, and don’t have money to give; what are you going to do about them? Aren’t they apart?\r\n\r\nThere are churches out there that the first thing they want to know is how much money you make. They’ll give you an application to fill out, and tell you what your dues are for the church. If you get behind, you get notices just like you do from companies. And don’t die or get sick, they’ll have your funeral at a funeral home and say you weren’t a member in good standing. That’s an organization and denomination for you.\r\n\r\nThere’s a saying that you’re suppose to give 10 percent in your offering. You don’t find 10 percent anywhere in the New Testament. The Bible tells us to give as the Lord has prospered you. There are people in the church that can afford to give more. That’s what He means by, “he that had gathered much had nothing over and he that had gathered little had no lack,” that there may be equality.\r\n\r\nWe have a cross- section of all types of people in the church. The Bible says give not grudgingly. You ever see some people saying, “I hate to give this” or “I don’t know what I should do" and taking three or four days to make up their mind? That is giving grudgingly.\r\n\r\nBut 2 Corinthians 9:6-7 tells us, God loveth a cheerful giver. If you give sparingly, expect little in return. What do you mean by sparingly? He means if you have it to give. Remember when Jesus was standing at the temple watching the Pharisees, the Sadducees put all kinds of money in. Then a little widow came up and put in a mite. Jesus stopped her and said, This widow has given more than them all because she gave everything she had. They gave out of their abundance.\r\n\r\nAfter you begin doing these things – the Seven Essentials – God is going to begin to open your eyes more because you’re faithful. The Bible tells us without a vision the people perish. When you do these things, you obligate God to work for you and open up your understanding. You obligate him when it comes to a revelation of the Body of Christ.', '7 Essentials of Faithfulness', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '7-essentials-of-faithfulness', '', '', '2013-07-16 21:59:55', '2013-07-17 04:59:55', '', 0, 'http://gac.bkc-stage.com/?post_type=messages&#038;p=172', 0, 'messages', '', 0),
